const add = (a = 2, b = 4) => a + b; 

console.log(add()); 
console.log(add(3)); 
console.log(add(null, 4)); 
console.log(add(undefined, 10));

Great example ðŸ‘Œ Letâ€™s break it down.

We have::::

const add = (a = 2, b = 4) => a + b;

console.log(add());           
console.log(add(3));          
console.log(add(null, 4));    
console.log(add(undefined, 10));

Step-by-step execution:

add()

No arguments passed.

Defaults: a = 2, b = 4.

2 + 4 = 6.
âœ… Output: 6

add(3)

a = 3, second argument missing â†’ b takes default 4.

3 + 4 = 7.
âœ… Output: 7

add(null, 4)

a = null (explicitly passed, so default is not applied).

b = 4.

null is coerced to 0 in numeric context.

0 + 4 = 4.
âœ… Output: 4

add(undefined, 10)

a = undefined (explicitly passed).

Default values in JS apply only if the argument is undefined.

So a becomes default 2.

b = 10.

2 + 10 = 12.
âœ… Output: 12
